balance	raw text	lender	doc	17	18	22	23	A synthetic securitisation is not open to the same misinterpretation because the original loans remain on the balance sheet of the original lender (the MFI), but it may conceal where the credit risk lies, which is important for financial stability purposes.																																		
balance	raw text	issued	doc	62	63	15	16	Furthermore, if the originating MFI, or the MFI sector as a whole, purchases the securities issued by the FVC acquiring the loans, it will appear (if the loans are mortgage or consumer credit loans, or loans to non-financial businesses) that there has been a switch from lending to households/non-financial corporations to credit to other financial intermediaries, which, although correct if the MFI balance sheet is considered in isolation, does not capture the economic reality of what has happened.																																		
balance	raw text	partner	doc	13	14	38	39	For various reasons, therefore, the information on the assets side of an MFI’s balance sheet needs to be supplemented, either by further information on its securitisation activities, which can be provided by the MFI itself, or by the partner FVC taking on the loans or assuming the credit risk, or some combination of the two.																																		
balance	raw text	holding	doc	17	18	26	27	Since synthetic securitisation is of no consequence from this perspective, because the loans remain on the originator’s balance sheet and the FVC does not record a holding of loans, the MFI balance sheet reporting does not contain special reporting requirements for synthetic securitisation (though, of course, any deposits placed by the FVC involved with the MFI in a synthetic securitisation as well as any FVC securities held by the MFI are included in the respective positions on the MFI balance sheet).																																		
balance	raw text	impact	doc	8	9	4	5	These operations have an impact on the MFI’s balance sheet similar to securitisation operations and are therefore also covered by the reporting requirements, as explained below.																																		
