security	raw text	down	doc	104	105	153	154	•	 Bad debt loans are loans whose repayment is overdue or which are otherwise identified as being impaired, partially or totally, in accordance with the definition of a default in Directive 2006/48/EC (Annex VII, Part 4, point 44): “A ‘default’ shall be considered to have occurred with regard to a particular obligor when either or both of the two following events has taken place: (a) the credit institution considers that the obligor is unlikely to pay its credit obligations to the credit institution, the parent undertaking or any of its subsidiaries in full, without recourse by the credit institution to actions such as realising security (if held); (b) the obligor is past due more than 90 days on any material credit obligation to the credit institution, the parent undertaking or any of its subsidiaries.” Bad debt loans are reported at their full amount on the MFI’s balance sheet unless they have been written down or written off.																																	
